Most SEO advice is written for small businesses with a single website and a handful of pages. That is not your world. If you are running SEO for an organisation with thousands (or millions) of URLs, multiple brands, distributed teams, and legacy infrastructure, you need an enterprise SEO consultant who understands how large organisations actually operate.

I am Sunny Patel, and I work with enterprise teams across the UK to build SEO programmes that scale. Not quick fixes — sustainable, governed, cross-functional strategies that survive reorgs, platform migrations, and shifting priorities.

## What makes enterprise SEO different

Enterprise SEO is not "normal SEO but bigger." The challenges are fundamentally different.

**Scale changes everything.** When your site has 50,000 or 5 million pages, you cannot manually optimise each one. You need templated solutions, automated auditing pipelines, and prioritisation frameworks that focus effort where it moves the needle. A single template change can affect hundreds of thousands of pages — for better or worse.

**Stakeholder complexity.** In a small business, the person who approves the SEO work is often the person who implements it. In an enterprise, you might need sign-off from product, engineering, legal, brand, and compliance before a title tag change goes live. The ability to build business cases, communicate in commercial terms, and navigate internal politics is as important as technical knowledge.

**Legacy technical debt.** Most enterprise sites have been through multiple redesigns, CMS migrations, and acquisitions. The result is layers of technical debt — orphaned URL structures, conflicting canonical strategies, inconsistent schema markup, and redirect chains that have been accumulating for a decade. Untangling this without breaking what already works requires careful, methodical execution.

**Governance gaps.** Without clear SEO governance, different teams publish content that cannibalises each other, developers push changes that break indexing, and brand guidelines conflict with search best practice. Enterprise SEO requires frameworks and documentation, not just recommendations.

## Common enterprise SEO challenges

These are the problems I see most often when working with large organisations.

**Site migrations gone wrong.** Enterprise migrations — whether replatforming, domain consolidation, or internationalisation — are high-risk events. I have seen migrations destroy years of organic growth because redirect mapping was incomplete, staging environments were accidentally indexed, or nobody tested how the new CMS handled pagination. I provide migration planning, risk assessment, and post-migration monitoring to protect your traffic.

**Multi-brand architecture.** When an organisation operates multiple brands, the question of domain strategy becomes critical. Separate domains, subdomains, or subdirectories? Shared link equity or isolated authority? These decisions have long-term consequences for crawl budget, brand authority, and content strategy. There is no universal answer — it depends on your commercial model.

**Cross-department coordination.** The SEO team wants to ship optimised landing pages. The dev team is mid-sprint on a product feature. The content team is writing for brand, not search. Legal needs to review every claim. Without a structured process, SEO work sits in backlogs indefinitely. I help teams build workflows that integrate SEO into existing processes rather than competing with them.

**Slow development cycles.** When engineering resources are scarce and release cycles are quarterly, you cannot afford to waste dev time on low-impact SEO tickets. I help prioritise technical recommendations by modelled impact, bundle changes into efficient deployment packages, and identify fixes that content or marketing teams can implement without engineering involvement.

## My enterprise SEO services

I offer a focused set of services designed for the realities of large-scale SEO.

**Technical audits at scale.** Not a generic crawl report — a prioritised, commercially-framed [technical SEO audit](/services/technical-seo-audit/) that accounts for your architecture, your tech stack, and your team's capacity. I use log file analysis, large-scale crawl data, and Core Web Vitals monitoring to identify the issues that actually affect rankings and revenue.

**Content governance.** I build content frameworks that prevent cannibalisation, enforce topical clustering, and align editorial output with search demand. This includes keyword mapping at scale, content lifecycle policies, and publishing guidelines that your content teams can follow independently. If you need to build genuine [topical authority](/services/topical-authority/) across competitive verticals, this is where it starts.

**Crawl budget management.** For sites with millions of URLs, how Google allocates crawl resources directly affects how quickly new content gets indexed and how efficiently changes propagate. I audit crawl waste — faceted navigation, parameter-based duplicates, thin index bloat — and implement controls that focus Googlebot on your highest-value pages.

**International SEO.** Multi-market, multi-language sites introduce hreflang complexity, duplicate content risk, and domain architecture decisions that most SEO consultants have never dealt with at scale. As an [international SEO consultant](/services/international-seo-consultant/), I have managed hreflang implementations across dozens of locales and resolved the indexing issues that come with them.

**Structured data across thousands of pages.** Schema markup at enterprise scale cannot be managed manually. I design templated structured data strategies — product, FAQ, article, organisation, breadcrumb — that deploy consistently across your site architecture and adapt as your content model evolves.

